title: Fix compilation errors for three CodeMirror addons
body:
I was seeing typescript throw this error when importing the `panel` `showhint` and `comment` addons:

`Invalid module name in augmentation. Module 'codemirror/addon/display/panel' resolves to an untyped module at '/absolute/path/to/node_modules/codemirror/addon/display/panel.js', which cannot be augmented.`

It seems like the cause of this issue is that you are not allowed to declare a **new** module in the same file as you are **augmenting** another module. One option was to move all the module declarations into a separate file, and then augment those in similar to what the [Ace editor project did](https://github.com/ajaxorg/ace/pull/3696). This approach doesn't work for codemirror because the addons are not full modules, so I have chosen the alternate approach of removing the module creation. It also doesn't work for codemirror because of the syntax that was chosen of `export = CodeMirror`, which the typescript compiler rejects as well. The addons still work, as the tests show.

title: Mongoose posthook overload
body:
Fixes incorrect selection of function overload in Mongoose post hooks.

Using the two-argument overload of the function **should** select an arity with the `mongoose.Document` first, and a `next()` handler after:

```ts
ExampleSchema.post('save', (doc: mongoose.Document, next: (err) => void) => { ... });
```

Currently, the order of the overloads causes the two-argument function to be interpreted as the three-argument overload, which places the arguments as error, document and next handler, respectively, and causes the following incorrect typing:

```ts
ExampleSchema.post('save', (doc: MongoError, next: mongoose.Document /*, (err) => void */) => { ... });
```

Switched order of function overloads and added types to test script for that function.

I wasn't able to find an open issue for this, but did locate another person who reported this same problem [on StackOverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/41155815/typescript-doesnt-select-the-correct-overload).

title: react-datepicker: Bump library version to 1.8 to prepare for 2.00
body:
react-datepicker recently released a 2.00 release with lots of breaking changes.  The current typings file is version 1.1. Before updating the typings version to 2.00, it makes sense to bring the current typings version up to 1.8 (the latest library version before 2.0) to make it easier for future pre-2.0 library users to find the correct typings version to use. 

To see why this is needed, imagine a future developer who is sticking with version 1.8 of the library because they want to defer rewriting their code from Moment to Date. If you're that developer, should you use version 1.1 or 2.0 of the typings?  If we bump the typings version to 1.8 before a future update to 2.0, then that choice is obvious.

This PR doesn't make any typings or tests changes-- it only bumps the library version in the first header line so that the version of the resulting @types/react-datepicker package will also be 1.8.

IMHO, the usual PR template steps don't apply because I'm not changing any typings or tests, only the library (and therefore the typings package) version number.

title: [WIP]: Get rid of that empty object in ReactFragment... which forced me to fix years of technical debt
body:
- [x] Use a meaningful title for the pull request. Include the name of the package modified.
- [ ] Test the change in your own code. (Compile and run.)
- [ ] Add or edit tests to reflect the change. (Run with `npm test`.)
- [x] Follow the advice from the [readme](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/blob/master/README.md#make-a-pull-request).
- [x] Avoid [common mistakes](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/blob/master/README.md#common-mistakes).
- [x] Run `npm run lint package-name` (or `tsc` if no `tslint.json` is present).

This one is going to be a doozy, and I'm pushing it in an incomplete state because it's being a pain to write so it'll probably be a pain to review too. I don't even know how many tests are still failing.

Backstory: that `{}` in the type of `ReactFragment`, combined with the `| null | undefined` in `ReactNode`, would allow anyone to pass literally anything as a child to a react component. That is not actually valid, and removing it caught several actual breaks or incorrect typedefs. That is the good part.

The bad part is, removing `{}` broke every single type definition that declares `children` as a render prop, because every component type declaration injects an `& { children?: ReactNode }` for convenience. This caused the function type to be `&`ed with `string`, `number`, `Array` et al but without having the one overload that would work, the `& {}` one; this creates an impossible type.

I tried to work around it through conditional types (`'children' extends keyof P ? P : P & { children?: ReactNode }`) but that broke assignability checks fierce in components that have generic props. This made it impossible to, for example, spread `...props` in child components, and no amount of casting short of `as any` could help.

The approach I have arrived on will unfortunately be breaking for a lot of old code, but it did allow me to finally fix a very old TODO to add correct variadic types to `createElement` (the same variadic types on `cloneElement` are TODO).

To minimize the effort of changing things, I decided to re-appropriate the very long deprecated `interface Props`. It can be extended or `&`ed as a shorthand to declare your `children` prop with the default type. But this can no longer be done magically, it has to be done on every component declaration that takes children.

Example of something that will break with this change:

```ts
interface FCProps {
  hidden: boolean;
}
const FC: React.FC<FCProps> = props => props.hidden ? null : props.children;
```

And this is its fixed version:

```ts
interface FCProps extends React.Props {
  hidden: boolean;
}
const FC: React.FC<FCProps> = props => props.hidden ? null : props.children;
```

As this touches a lot of deep technical debt, this is also allowing me to fix the type of `ReactNode` to no longer allow `undefined` (you can't return `undefined` from `render()`; fixing that forced me to fix that type) and also touch on the `ReactElement` types.

This PR is being very hard to work on as every little change breaks something somewhere and fixing _that_ breaks something elsewhere. I had to pick the one breaking change that would be best looking forward, even if it requires some churn.

---

I wish there was a way to know how much of these old types (like `CElement` et al) are still used so I can have an idea on the scope of how much things would break if `ReactElement` was completely overhauled. Is `createFactory` even still a thing?

EDIT: `createFactory` is a thing, but `ReactDOM`, `ReactHTML` and `ReactSVG` should no longer be things because they're only there because of the old `React.DOM` object that was removed on React 16. I could remove them now... `ComponentProps<'element name'>` is a better replacement 🤔
